OL,3,CSex offence anonymity law ruled
OL,4,C'incompatible with press freedom'
OL,6,FDisputing any justification for the
OL,7,Fclause, lawyers representing the media
OL,8,Forganisations argued that the
OL,9,F"sweeping impact" of the restrictions
OL,10,Ffailed to properly balance the wider
OL,11,Finterest in bringing information to
OL,12,Fthe public's attention through
OL,13,Finvestigative journalism.
OL,15,FCounsel for the Department responded
OL,16,Fthat the press were seeking a radical
OL,17,Fremedy of having legislation declared
OL,18,Fso fundamentally flawed that it should
OL,19,Fbe expunged.
