OL,3,CSex offence anonymity law ruled
OL,4,C'incompatible with press freedom'
OL,6,FRuling on the challenge, Mr Justice
OL,7,FHumphreys stressed: "The imposition of
OL,8,Fa criminal sanction on public interest
OL,9,Fjournalism, and the chilling effect
OL,10,Foccasioned thereby, represents an
OL,11,Finterference with an Article 10 right
OL,12,Fwhich requires the most anxious
OL,13,Fscrutiny."
OL,15,FHe held that editors and broadcasters
OL,16,Fshould not be exposed to the threat of
OL,17,Fprosecution and conviction without an
OL,18,Fopportunity to make the case that it
OL,19,Fwas in the public interest to name a
OL,20,Fsuspected sex offender.
